dwork at fish markets and fishing ports in Japan, North America, Korea, and Europe—explains the complex social institutions that organize Tsukiji's auctions and the supply lines leading to and from them and illuminates trends of Japan's economic growth, changes in distribution and consumption, and the increasing globalization of the seafood trade. As he brings to life the sights and sounds of the marketplace, he reveals Tsukiji's rich internal culture, its place in Japanese cuisine, and the mercantile traditions that have shaped the marketplace since the early seventeenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMarketszJapanzTokyoxHistory. 0aSeafood industryzJapanzTokyoxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a17th century.  aasian culture.  aasian history.  acase study.  aeast asia.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  aethnography.  afieldwork.  afishmonger.  afoodways.  aglobalization.  ainternational.  ajapan.  ajapanese culture.  ajapanese food.  amarketplace.  apublic health.  aseafood trade.  aseafood.  asushi chef.  asushi.  atechnology.  atokyo.  atourism.  atourist trap.  atourist.  atsukiji.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022023240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092358440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520923584423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520923584/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY